 17              return float(text) 
 18          except ValueError:

 20                  import struct 
 21                  return struct.unpack('d', struct.pack('Q', 0xfff8000000000000))[0]

 26 -def parse_basics(lines, results): 

 27      """Parse the basic information that should be present in most codeml output files.""" 
 28      # multi_models is used to designate there being results for more than one 
 29      # model in the file 
 30      multi_models = False 
 31      multi_genes = False 
 32      version_re = re.compile(".+ \(in paml version (\d+\.\d+[a-z]*).*") 
 33      model_re = re.compile("Model:\s+(.+)") 
 34      num_genes_re = re.compile("\(([0-9]+) genes: separate data\)") 
 35      # In codeml 4.1, the codon substitution model is headed by: 
 36      # "Codon frequencies:" 
 37      # In codeml 4.3+ it is headed by: 
 38      # "Codon frequency model:" 
 39      codon_freq_re = re.compile("Codon frequenc[a-z\s]{3,7}:\s+(.+)") 
 40      siteclass_re = re.compile("Site-class models:\s*([^\s]*)") 
 41      for line in lines: 
 42          # Find all floating point numbers in this line 
 43          line_floats_res = line_floats_re.findall(line) 
 44          line_floats = [_nan_float(val) for val in line_floats_res] 
 45          # Get the program version number 
 46          version_res = version_re.match(line) 
 47          if version_res is not None: 
 48              results["version"] = version_res.group(1) 
 49              continue 
 50          # Find the model description at the beginning of the file. 
 51          model_res = model_re.match(line) 
 52          if model_res is not None: 
 53              results["model"] = model_res.group(1) 
 54          # Find out if more than one genes are analyzed 
 55          num_genes_res = num_genes_re.search(line) 
 56          if num_genes_res is not None: 
 57              results["genes"] = [] 
 58              num_genes = int(num_genes_res.group(1)) 
 59              for n in range(num_genes): 
 60                  results["genes"].append({}) 
 61              multi_genes = True 
 62              continue 
 63          # Get the codon substitution model 
 64          codon_freq_res = codon_freq_re.match(line) 
 65          if codon_freq_res is not None: 
 66              results["codon model"] = codon_freq_res.group(1) 
 67              continue 
 68          # Find the site-class model name at the beginning of the file. 
 69          # This exists only if a NSsites class other than 0 is used. 
 70          # If there's no site class model listed, then there are multiple 
 71          # models in the results file 
 72          # Example match: "Site-class models:  PositiveSelection" 
 73          siteclass_res = siteclass_re.match(line) 
 74          if siteclass_res is not None: 
 75              siteclass_model = siteclass_res.group(1) 
 76              if siteclass_model != "": 
 77                  results["site-class model"] = siteclass_model 
 78                  multi_models = False 
 79              else: 
 80                  multi_models = True 
 81          # Get the maximum log-likelihood 
 82          if "ln Lmax" in line and line_floats: 
 83              results["lnL max"] = line_floats[0] 
 84      return (results, multi_models, multi_genes)

 88      """Determine which NSsites models are present and parse them.""" 
 89      ns_sites = {} 
 90      model_re = re.compile("Model (\d+):\s+(.+)") 
 91      gene_re = re.compile("Gene\s+([0-9]+)\s+.+") 
 92      siteclass_model = results.get("site-class model") 
 93      if not multi_models: 
 94          # If there's only one model in the results, find out 
 95          # which one it is and then parse it. 
 96          if siteclass_model is None: 
 97              siteclass_model = "one-ratio" 
 98          current_model = {"one-ratio": 0, 
 99                           "NearlyNeutral": 1, 
100                           "PositiveSelection": 2, 
101                           "discrete": 3, 
102                           "beta": 7, 
103                           "beta&w>1": 8, 
104                           "M2a_rel": 22}[siteclass_model] 
105          if multi_genes: 
106              genes = results["genes"] 
107              current_gene = None 
108              gene_start = None 
109              model_results = None 
110              for line_num, line in enumerate(lines): 
111                  gene_res = gene_re.match(line) 
112                  if gene_res: 
113                      if current_gene is not None: 
114                          assert model_results is not None 
115                          parse_model(lines[gene_start:line_num], model_results) 
116                          genes[current_gene - 1] = model_results 
117                      gene_start = line_num 
118                      current_gene = int(gene_res.group(1)) 
119                      model_results = {"description": siteclass_model} 
120              if len(genes[current_gene - 1]) == 0: 
121                  model_results = parse_model(lines[gene_start:], model_results) 
122                  genes[current_gene - 1] = model_results 
123          else: 
124              model_results = {"description": siteclass_model} 
125              model_results = parse_model(lines, model_results) 
126              ns_sites[current_model] = model_results 
127      else: 
128          # If there are multiple models in the results, scan through 
129          # the file and send each model's text to be parsed individually. 
130          current_model = None 
131          model_start = None 
132          for line_num, line in enumerate(lines): 
133              # Find model names. If this is found on a line, 
134              # all of the following lines until the next time this matches 
135              # contain results for Model X. 
136              # Example match: "Model 1: NearlyNeutral (2 categories)" 
137              model_res = model_re.match(line) 
138              if model_res: 
139                  if current_model is not None: 
140                      # We've already been tracking a model, so it's time 
141                      # to send those lines off for parsing before beginning 
142                      # a new one. 
143                      parse_model(lines[model_start:line_num], model_results) 
144                      ns_sites[current_model] = model_results 
145                  model_start = line_num 
146                  current_model = int(model_res.group(1)) 
147                  model_results = {"description": model_res.group(2)} 
148          if ns_sites.get(current_model) is None: 
149              # When we reach the end of the file, we'll still have one more 
150              # model to parse. 
151              model_results = parse_model(lines[model_start:], model_results) 
152              ns_sites[current_model] = model_results 
153      # Only add the ns_sites dict to the results if we really have results. 
154      # Model M0 is added by default in some cases, so if it exists, make sure 
155      # it's not empty 
156      if len(ns_sites) == 1: 
157          m0 = ns_sites.get(0) 
158          if not m0 or len(m0) > 1: 
159              results["NSsites"] = ns_sites 
160      elif len(ns_sites) > 1: 
161          results["NSsites"] = ns_sites 
162      return results

166      """Parse an individual NSsites model's results."""

170      dN_tree_flag = False 
171      w_tree_flag = False 
172      num_params = None 
173      tree_re = re.compile("^\([\w #:',.()]*\);\s*$")

175      model_params_re = re.compile("(?<!\S)([a-z]\d?)\s*=\s+(\d+\.\d+)") 
176      for line in lines:

178          line_floats_res = line_floats_re.findall(line) 
179          line_floats = [_nan_float(val) for val in line_floats_res] 
180          # Check if branch-specific results are in the line 
181          branch_res = branch_re.match(line) 
182          # Check if additional model parameters are in the line 
183          model_params = model_params_re.findall(line) 
184          # Find lnL values.

186          # "lnL(ntime: 19  np: 22):  -2021.348300      +0.000000"

189              np_res = re.match("lnL\(ntime:\s+\d+\s+np:\s+(\d+)\)", line) 
190              if np_res is not None: 
191                  num_params = int(np_res.group(1)) 
192          # Get parameter list. This can be useful for specifying starting 
193          # parameters in another run by copying the list of parameters 
194          # to a file called in.codeml. Since the parameters must be in 
195          # a fixed order and format, copying and pasting to the file is 
196          # best. For this reason, they are grabbed here just as a long 
197          # string and not as individual numbers. 
198          elif len(line_floats) == num_params and not SEs_flag: 
199              parameters["parameter list"] = line.strip() 
200          # Find SEs. The same format as parameters above is maintained 
201          # since there is a correspondence between the SE format and 
202          # the parameter format. 
203          # Example match: 
204          # "SEs for parameters: 
205          # -1.00000 -1.00000 -1.00000 801727.63247 730462.67590 -1.00000 
206          elif "SEs for parameters:" in line: 
207              SEs_flag = True 
208          elif SEs_flag and len(line_floats) == num_params: 
209              parameters["SEs"] = line.strip() 
210              SEs_flag = False 
211          # Find tree lengths. 
212          # Example match: "tree length =   1.71931" 
213          elif "tree length =" in line and line_floats: 
214              results["tree length"] = line_floats[0] 
215          # Find the estimated trees only taking the tree if it has 
216          # lengths or rate estimates on the branches 
217          elif tree_re.match(line) is not None: 
218              if ":" in line or "#" in line: 
219                  if dS_tree_flag: 
220                      results["dS tree"] = line.strip() 
221                      dS_tree_flag = False 
222                  elif dN_tree_flag: 
223                      results["dN tree"] = line.strip() 
224                      dN_tree_flag = False 
225                  elif w_tree_flag: 
226                      results["omega tree"] = line.strip() 
227                      w_tree_flag = False 
228                  else: 
229                      results["tree"] = line.strip() 
230          elif "dS tree:" in line: 
231              dS_tree_flag = True 
232          elif "dN tree:" in line:

234          elif "w ratios as labels for TreeView:" in line:

236          # Find rates for multiple genes 
237          # Example match: "rates for 2 genes:     1  2.75551" 
238          elif "rates for" in line and line_floats: 
239              line_floats.insert(0, 1.0) 
240              parameters["rates"] = line_floats 
241          # Find kappa values. 
242          # Example match: "kappa (ts/tv) =  2.77541" 
243          elif "kappa (ts/tv)" in line and line_floats: 
244              parameters["kappa"] = line_floats[0] 
245          # Find omega values. 
246          # Example match: "omega (dN/dS) =  0.25122" 
247          elif "omega (dN/dS)" in line and line_floats: 
248              parameters["omega"] = line_floats[0] 
249          elif "w (dN/dS)" in line and line_floats: 
250              parameters["omega"] = line_floats 
251          # Find omega and kappa values for multi-gene files 
252          # Example match: "gene # 1: kappa =   1.72615 omega =   0.39333" 
253          elif "gene # " in line: 
254              gene_num = int(re.match("gene # (\d+)", line).group(1)) 
255              if parameters.get("genes") is None: 
256                  parameters["genes"] = {} 
257              parameters["genes"][gene_num] = {"kappa": line_floats[0], 
258                                               "omega": line_floats[1]} 
259          # Find dN values. 
260          # Example match: "tree length for dN:       0.2990" 
261          elif "tree length for dN" in line and line_floats: 
262              parameters["dN"] = line_floats[0] 
263          # Find dS values 
264          # Example match: "tree length for dS:       1.1901" 
265          elif "tree length for dS" in line and line_floats: 
266              parameters["dS"] = line_floats[0] 
267          # Find site class distributions. 
268          # Example match 1 (normal model, 2 site classes): 
269          # "p:   0.77615  0.22385" 
270          # Example match 2 (branch site A model, 4 site classes): 
271          # "proportion       0.00000  0.00000  0.73921  0.26079" 
272          elif line[0:2] == "p:" or line[0:10] == "proportion": 
273              site_classes = parse_siteclass_proportions(line_floats) 
274              parameters["site classes"] = site_classes 
275          # Find the omega value corresponding to each site class 
276          # Example match (2 site classes): "w:   0.10224  1.00000" 
277          elif line[0:2] == "w:": 
278              site_classes = parameters.get("site classes") 
279              site_classes = parse_siteclass_omegas(line, site_classes) 
280              parameters["site classes"] = site_classes 
281          # Find the omega values corresponding to a branch type from 
282          # the clade model C for each site class 
283          # Example match: 
284          # "branch type 0:    0.31022   1.00000   0.00000" 
285          elif "branch type " in line: 
286              branch_type = re.match("branch type (\d)", line) 
287              if branch_type:

293          # Find the omega values of the foreground branch for each site

295          # Example match: 
296          # "foreground w     0.07992  1.00000 134.54218 134.54218" 
297          elif line[0:12] == "foreground w": 
298              site_classes = parameters.get("site classes") 
299              site_classes = parse_branch_site_a(True, line_floats, site_classes) 
300              parameters["site classes"] = site_classes 
301          # Find the omega values of the background for each site 
302          # class in the branch site A model 
303          # Example match: 
304          # "background w     0.07992  1.00000  0.07992  1.00000" 
305          elif line[0:12] == "background w": 
306              site_classes = parameters.get("site classes") 
307              site_classes = parse_branch_site_a(False, line_floats, site_classes) 
308              parameters["site classes"] = site_classes 
309          # Find dN & dS for each branch, which is organized in a table 
310          # The possibility of NaNs forces me to not use the line_floats 
311          # method. 
312          # Example row (some spaces removed to make it smaller...). 
313          # " 6..7   0.000  167.7  54.3  0.0000  0.0000  0.0000  0.0  0.0" 
314          elif branch_res is not None and line_floats: 
315              branch = branch_res.group(1) 
316              if parameters.get("branches") is None: 
317                  parameters["branches"] = {} 
318              # Hack for Jython http://bugs.jython.org/issue1762 float("-nan") 
319              line = line.replace(" -nan", " nan") 
320              params = line.strip().split()[1:] 
321              parameters["branches"][branch] = { 
322                  "t": _nan_float(params[0].strip()),

330          # Find model parameters, which can be spread across multiple

332          # Example matches:

334          # "  (p1=  0.00957) w=  3.25530" 
335          elif model_params: 
336              float_model_params = []

358 -def parse_siteclass_omegas(line, site_classes): 

359      """Find omega estimate for each class. 
360   
361      For models which have multiple site classes, find the omega estimated 
362      for each class. 
363      """ 
364      # The omega results are tabular with strictly 9 characters per column 
365      # (1 to 3 digits before the  decimal point and 5 after). This causes 
366      # numbers to sometimes run into each other, so we must use a different 
367      # regular expression to account for this. i.e.: 
368      # w:   0.00012  1.00000109.87121 
369      line_floats = re.findall("\d{1,3}\.\d{5}", line) 
370      if not site_classes or len(line_floats) == 0: 
371          return 
372      for n in range(len(line_floats)): 
373          site_classes[n]["omega"] = line_floats[n] 
374      return site_classes

402 -def parse_pairwise(lines, results): 

403      """Parse results from pairwise comparisons.""" 
404      # Find pairwise comparisons 
405      # Example: 
406      # 2 (Pan_troglo) ... 1 (Homo_sapie) 
407      # lnL = -291.465693 
408      #  0.01262 999.00000  0.00100 
409      # 
410      # t= 0.0126  S=    81.4  N=   140.6  dN/dS= 0.0010  dN= 0.0000  dS= 0.0115 
411      pair_re = re.compile("\d+ \((.+)\) ... \d+ \((.+)\)") 
412      pairwise = {} 
413      seq1 = None 
414      seq2 = None 
415      for line in lines: 
416          # Find all floating point numbers in this line 
417          line_floats_res = line_floats_re.findall(line) 
418          line_floats = [_nan_float(val) for val in line_floats_res] 
419          pair_res = pair_re.match(line) 
420          if pair_res: 
421              seq1 = pair_res.group(1) 
422              seq2 = pair_res.group(2) 
423              if seq1 not in pairwise: 
424                  pairwise[seq1] = {} 
425              if seq2 not in pairwise: 
426                  pairwise[seq2] = {} 
427          if len(line_floats) == 1 and seq1 is not None and seq2 is not None: 
428              pairwise[seq1][seq2] = {"lnL": line_floats[0]} 
429              pairwise[seq2][seq1] = pairwise[seq1][seq2] 
430          elif len(line_floats) == 6 and seq1 is not None and seq2 is not None: 
431              pairwise[seq1][seq2].update({"t": line_floats[0], 
432                                           "S": line_floats[1], 
433                                           "N": line_floats[2], 
434                                           "omega": line_floats[3], 
435                                           "dN": line_floats[4], 
436                                           "dS": line_floats[5]}) 
437              pairwise[seq2][seq1] = pairwise[seq1][seq2] 
438      if pairwise: 
439          results["pairwise"] = pairwise 
440      return results

443 -def parse_distances(lines, results): 

444      """Parse amino acid sequence distance results.""" 
445      distances = {} 
446      sequences = [] 
447      raw_aa_distances_flag = False 
448      ml_aa_distances_flag = False 
449      matrix_row_re = re.compile("(.+)\s{5,15}") 
450      for line in lines: 
451          # Find all floating point numbers in this line 
452          line_floats_res = line_floats_re.findall(line) 
453          line_floats = [_nan_float(val) for val in line_floats_res] 
454          if "AA distances" in line: 
455              raw_aa_distances_flag = True 
456              # In current versions, the raw distances always come 
457              # first but I don't trust this to always be true 
458              ml_aa_distances_flag = False 
459          elif "ML distances of aa seqs." in line: 
460              ml_aa_distances_flag = True 
461              raw_aa_distances_flag = False 
462          # Parse AA distances (raw or ML), in a lower diagonal matrix 
463          matrix_row_res = matrix_row_re.match(line) 
464          if matrix_row_res and (raw_aa_distances_flag or 
465                                 ml_aa_distances_flag): 
466              seq_name = matrix_row_res.group(1).strip() 
467              if seq_name not in sequences: 
468                  sequences.append(seq_name) 
469              if raw_aa_distances_flag: 
470                  if distances.get("raw") is None: 
471                      distances["raw"] = {} 
472                  distances["raw"][seq_name] = {} 
473                  for i in range(0, len(line_floats)): 
474                      distances["raw"][seq_name][sequences[i]] = line_floats[i] 
475                      distances["raw"][sequences[i]][seq_name] = line_floats[i] 
476              else: 
477                  if distances.get("ml") is None: 
478                      distances["ml"] = {} 
479                  distances["ml"][seq_name] = {} 
480                  for i in range(0, len(line_floats)): 
481                      distances["ml"][seq_name][sequences[i]] = line_floats[i] 
482                      distances["ml"][sequences[i]][seq_name] = line_floats[i] 
483      if distances: 
484          results["distances"] = distances 
485      return results
